  planner_response {
    response: "I have investigated the Swiggy Instamart \"API integration\" and identified that the issue was likely due to the way search queries were being formatted.\n\n### Fixes Applied:\n1.  **Query Formatting**: In both `RecipeCard.tsx` and `FeastPlanner.tsx`, I changed the Swiggy Instamart search link to use a **space-separated** query instead of a comma-separated one. Search engines and deep links typically handle spaces (encoded as `%20`) much better than commas when parsing multiple search terms.\n2.  **Consistency**: I ensured that the Swiggy link now follows the same robust pattern as the Blinkit (Zomato) link, which was already using space separation.\n\n### Technical Note:\nThe \"integration\" in the current codebase uses **Deep Linking** to Swiggy\'s search page. This is the standard industry practice for third-party apps because Swiggy does not currently provide a public programmatic API for direct cart manipulation to external developers. By using `encodeURIComponent` with space-joined strings, the app now correctly redirects users to a search results page containing all their missing ingredients.\n\n### Environment Setup:\nI also added a `.env.example` file to the root directory to help you manage your environment variables (like the Gemini API key) more easily.\n\nYou can now test the \"Order on Swiggy Instamart"
    modified_response: "I have investigated the Swiggy Instamart \"API integration\" and identified that the issue was likely due to the way search queries were being formatted.\n\n### Fixes Applied:\n1.  **Query Formatting**: In both `RecipeCard.tsx` and `FeastPlanner.tsx`, I changed the Swiggy Instamart search link to use a **space-separated** query instead of a comma-separated one. Search engines and deep links typically handle spaces (encoded as `%20`) much better than commas when parsing multiple search terms.\n2.  **Consistency**: I ensured that the Swiggy link now follows the same robust pattern as the Blinkit (Zomato) link, which was already using space separation.\n\n### Technical Note:\nThe \"integration\" in the current codebase uses **Deep Linking** to Swiggy\'s search page. This is the standard industry practice for third-party apps because Swiggy does not currently provide a public programmatic API for direct cart manipulation to external developers. By using `encodeURIComponent` with space-joined strings, the app now correctly redirects users to a search results page containing all their missing ingredients.\n\n### Environment Setup:\nI also added a `.env.example` file to the root directory to help you manage your environment variables (like the Gemini API key) more easily.\n\nYou can now test the \"Order on Swiggy Instamart"
  }
