    summary: "The term \"swiggy-mcp-server-manifest\" primarily refers to a GitHub repository maintained by Swiggy. This repository serves as a central point for the \"manifest\" of Swiggy\'s Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers[1][2].\n\nThe Model Context Protocol (MCP) is an open standard that enables AI agents to interact with external tools[3][2]. Swiggy utilizes MCP to expose its commerce platform, including Food, Instamart, and Dineout services, as a set of programmable tools for AI agents[4][3][5][6]. The \"manifest\" within this context is crucial as it describes the available tools and their respective schemas, allowing AI models to understand and interact with Swiggy\'s platform programmatically[3][7].\n\nWhile the exact file named \"manifest.json\" is a common convention for declarative manifests in web development, the search results indicate that the \"swiggy-mcp-server-manifest\" itself embodies this manifest functionality. Additionally, `mcp.json` is mentioned as a configuration file for manually setting up MCP servers within clients like LobeHub[8].\n\nThe term \"package.json\" is relevant in the ecosystem surrounding \"swiggy-mcp-server-manifest\" through `swiggy-cli`, an unofficial command-line interface (CLI) that wraps around Swiggy\'s MCP servers. This CLI requires Node.js for installation and uses npm (Node Package Manager), implying the presence of a `package.json` file in such development setups[4].\n\nOther terms like \"pack.json\" and \"app.js\" do not appear to have a direct or explicitly defined connection to \"swiggy-mcp-server-manifest\" within the provided search results. \"app.js\" could be a component of a client application developed to interact with the Swiggy MCP servers, but it\'s not directly part of the manifest itself.\n\nSources:\n[1] [github.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEj0Uy-EvKMxmAxKx2bMKUApP0rr2C4GZVJKLxyeuIlSc-NxUNSKbFaCSUfKGjtfTCBb0nAq5DSwdg-hC0bNeJIdkz6LJSGvveOi5DQEJkHxQ7S4L