  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Discovering Swiggy Setup**\n\nI\'ve struck gold! The eighth search result leads to a Github link detailing the setup of the Swiggy MCP server. According to the configuration, it\'s initiated using `npx -y swiggy-mcp-server`.\n\n\n**Analyzing Server Capabilities**\n\nOkay, I\'ve got a clearer picture now. The server supports Swiggy Food, Instamart, and Dineout, using OAuth for authentication. Crucially, the local MCP client can be configured to interact with the Swiggy server. I\'m noting the available tools: `instamart.search_items`, `instamart.add_to_cart`, `instamart.get_cart`, and `instamart.checkout`. This is definitely powerful; however, I will need to consider the next user prompt in more detail.\n\n\n**Clarifying Implementation Strategy**\n\nI\'m now focusing on how the Swiggy MCP Server can best be utilized and explained to the user. I\'ve realized it\'s a *local* tool server, which is key. The AI model running on the user\'s side invokes the server. I will work on a complete guide and integration support that describes connecting the Swiggy MCP Server to the user\'s AI workbench. I\'m also planning to add a new \"Export to Swiggy MCP Workspace\" feature to export ingredient lists in a user-friendly format, potentially JSON or formatted text, for LLMs equipped with the Swiggy MCP.\n\n\n**Refining Integration Approach**\n\nI\'ve hit a breakthrough! I\'m now exploring a direct integration path. A \"Copy Swiggy MCP prompt\" feature within the recipe and planner components will provide a polished instruction. My focus is on creating a beautiful guide for setting up the Swiggy MCP Server for various environments like Claude Desktop or Cursor. This is going to solve the Swiggy Instamart problem perfectly, and utilize the latest tools, in a streamlined flow for the user.\n\n\n**Evaluating Prompt Intent**\n\nI\'m now diving deep into the user\'s \"Order on Swiggy Instamart\" issue. The prompt is clear; they want to use the Swiggy MCP server. However, I\'m stuck because I realize I\'m running in a Cloud Run container without a local MCP host, and all my tools are system-level. I\'m exploring whether the user wants me to write a script, integrate the MCP client, add documentation, or design an interactive UI element within `RecipeCard.tsx` and `FeastPlanner.tsx` to facilitate this integration.\n\n\n**Designing UI Integration**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a UI integration plan. I will offer a third option: \"Order via Swiggy MCP (AI Assistant).\" Clicking it will launch a card, explaining the AI setup with a code snippet. A \"Copy AI Prompt\" button pre-formats the missing items for a Swiggy MCP call. I\'m confirming this design now, as this solves the user\'s need perfectly.\n\n\n**Implementing UI Action**\n\nI\'m now thinking about UI implementation, and I\'ve decided to incorporate both the direct Instamart link and the AI Assistant integration directly into the `RecipeCard.tsx` and `FeastPlanner.tsx`. The new button will trigger a Swiggy MCP guide and prompt display, providing users a choice. This will offer streamlined ordering for the user.\n\n\n\n**Designing Guide Component**\n\nI\'m now focusing on building the Swiggy MCP Guide as a reusable modal. I\'m structuring the code in a modular fashion, creating a new `/components/SwiggyMcpGuide.tsx` file for this component. This helper will receive `isOpen`, `onClose`, and `missingItems`, and will display a user-friendly modal with setup steps for the Swiggy MCP Server.\n\n\n**Constructing Guide Modal**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in building the `SwiggyMcpGuide` component. I\'m focusing on simplicity: no external packages, pure client-side React. The guide will include clear setup steps: first, to install the server locally with `npx -y swiggy-mcp-server`. I will include a configuration snippet the user needs, and a prompt for their AI to use, all with \"Copy\" buttons. I\'ve switched to `lucide-react` icons for styling, and I\'m ensuring everything aligns with existing style guidelines. I\'m thinking about including an icon list to check for available icons within the `lucide-react` library.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 15
      nanos: 45775559
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
